This is a 52-year-old male being seen in our downtown office because of pain in his left groin. He underwent EVAR on 2022-08-29 by Dr. Dwivedi. He was discharged home the following day on 2022-08-30. He came to the emergency room on 2022-08-31 with left groin pain. He had left groin duplex which was negative for pseudoaneurysm. He is now being seen in my office today with continued left groin pain. On examination his left groin has diffuse ecchymosis. It is exquisitely tender to touch. He is unable to walk because of the pain. He has petechial spotting to his right groin.On 2022-04-18 he underwent right TCAR. On 2022-06-06 he underwent left common carotid artery to internal carotid artery bypass. He is taking Plavix and statin therapy.
Patient with left groin hematoma. I have reviewed his chart which indicates he has chronic thrombocytopenia. In discussion with patient he does not know why he has this. Given the fact that he is unable to ambulate due to the pain in the hematoma coupled with his low platelets my recommendation would be inpatient admission to the hospital where we can monitor for swelling of his groin. I will get baseline labs to monitor his platelets and hemoglobin. We will ask hematology to see him to work-up his low platelets. Will provide pain control as well. Patient is agreeable with this plan. Case discussed with Dr. Dwivedi as well.

Throughout his admission, pain controlled with oral pain meds. He has been able to ambulate with difficulty. Dr. Amin consulted for medical management. Dr. Bhimani consulted for elevated Cr- appeared to be stable and renal work-up completed while IP. He is to f/u with Dr. Bhimani in 4-6 weeks. Hematology also saw him for thrombocytopenia. Labs were drawn and recs noted. Workup to include labs and abd US. If stable for d/c, this can be completed as outpatient. Will have him f/u as OP. Pt verbalized readiness to go home and assume self-care.

Coronary Artery Disease, Male
Coronary artery disease (CAD) is a condition in which the arteries that lead to the heart (coronary arteries) become narrow or blocked. The narrowing or blockage can lead to decreased blood flow to the heart. Prolonged reduced blood flow can cause a heart attack (myocardial infarction or MI). This condition may also be called coronary heart disease.
Because CAD is the leading cause of death in men, it is important to understand what causes this condition and how it is treated.
What are the causes?
CAD is most often caused by atherosclerosis. This is the buildup of fat and cholesterol (plaque) on the inside of the arteries. Over time, the plaque may narrow or block the artery, reducing blood flow to the heart. Plaque can also become weak and break off within a coronary artery and cause a sudden blockage. Other less common causes of CAD include:
• A blood clot or a piece of a blood clot or other substance that blocks the flow of blood in a coronary artery (embolism).
• A tearing of the artery (spontaneous coronary artery dissection).
• An enlargement of an artery (aneurysm).
• Inflammation (vasculitis) in the artery wall.
What increases the risk?
The following factors may make you more likely to develop this condition:
• Age. Men over age 45 are at a greater risk of CAD.
• Family history of CAD.
• Gender. Men often develop CAD earlier in life than women.
• High blood pressure (hypertension).
• Diabetes.
• High cholesterol levels.
• Tobacco use.
• Excessive alcohol use.
• Lack of exercise.
• A diet high in saturated and trans fats, such as fried food and processed meat.
Other possible risk factors include:
• High stress levels.
• Depression.
• Obesity.
• Sleep apnea.
What are the signs or symptoms?
Many people do not have any symptoms during the early stages of CAD. As the condition progresses, symptoms may include:
• Chest pain (angina). The pain can:
◦ Feel like crushing or squeezing, or like a tightness, pressure, fullness, or heaviness in the chest.
◦ Last more than a few minutes or can stop and recur. The pain tends to get worse with exercise or stress and to fade with rest.
• Pain in the arms, neck, jaw, ear, or back.
• Unexplained heartburn or indigestion.
• Shortness of breath.
• Nausea or vomiting.
• Sudden light-headedness.
• Sudden cold sweats.
• Fluttering or fast heartbeat (palpitations).
How is this diagnosed?
This condition is diagnosed based on:
• Your family and medical history.
• A physical exam.
• Tests, including:
◦ A test to check the electrical signals in your heart (electrocardiogram).
◦ Exercise stress test. This looks for signs of blockage when the heart is stressed with exercise, such as running on a treadmill.
◦ Pharmacologic stress test. This test looks for signs of blockage when the heart is being stressed with a medicine.
◦ Blood tests.
◦ Coronary angiogram. This is a procedure to look at the coronary arteries to see if there is any blockage. During this test, a dye is injected into your arteries so they appear on an X-ray.
◦ Coronary artery CT scan. This CT scan helps detect calcium deposits in your coronary arteries. Calcium deposits are an indicator of CAD.
◦ A test that uses sound waves to take a picture of your heart (echocardiogram).
◦ Chest X-ray.
How is this treated?
This condition may be treated by:
• Healthy lifestyle changes to reduce risk factors.
• Medicines such as:
◦ Antiplatelet medicines and blood-thinning medicines, such as aspirin. These help to prevent blood clots.
◦ Nitroglycerin.
◦ Blood pressure medicines.
◦ Cholesterol-lowering medicine.
• Coronary angioplasty and stenting. During this procedure, a thin, flexible tube is inserted through a blood vessel and into a blocked artery. A balloon or similar device on the end of the tube is inflated to open up the artery. In some cases, a small, mesh tube (stent) is inserted into the artery to keep it open.
• Coronary artery bypass surgery. During this surgery, veins or arteries from other parts of the body are used to create a bypass around the blockage and allow blood to reach your heart.
Follow these instructions at home:
Medicines
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your health care provider.
• Do not take the following medicines unless your health care provider approves:
◦ NSAIDs, such as ibuprofen, naproxen, or celecoxib.
◦ Vitamin supplements that contain vitamin A, vitamin E, or both.
Lifestyle
• Follow an exercise program approved by your health care provider. Aim for 150 minutes of moderate exercise or 75 minutes of vigorous exercise each week.
• Maintain a healthy weight or lose weight as approved by your health care provider.
• Learn to manage stress or try to limit your stress. Ask your health care provider for suggestions if you need help.
• Get screened for depression and seek treatment, if needed.
• Do not use any products that contain nicotine or tobacco, such as cigarettes, e-cigarettes, and chewing tobacco. If you need help quitting, ask your health care provider.
• Do not use illegal drugs.
Eating and drinking
• Follow a heart-healthy diet. A dietitian can help educate you about healthy food options and changes. In general, eat plenty of fruits and vegetables, lean meats, and whole grains.
• Avoid foods high in:
◦ Sugar.
◦ Salt (sodium).
◦ Saturated fat, such as processed or fatty meat.
◦ Trans fat, such as fried foods.
• Use healthy cooking methods such as roasting, grilling, broiling, baking, poaching, steaming, or stir-frying.
• Do not drink alcohol if your health care provider tells you not to drink.
• If you drink alcohol:
◦ Limit how much you have to 0–2 drinks per day.
◦ Be aware of how much alcohol is in your drink. In the U.S., one drink equals one 12 oz bottle of beer (355 mL), one 5 oz glass of wine (148 mL), or one 1½ oz glass of hard liquor (44 mL).
General instructions
• Manage any other health conditions, such as hypertension and diabetes. These conditions affect your heart.
• Your health care provider may ask you to monitor your blood pressure. Ideally, your blood pressure should be below 130/80.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your health care provider. This is important.
Get help right away if:
• You have pain in your chest, neck, ear, arm, jaw, stomach, or back that:
◦ Lasts more than a few minutes.
◦ Is recurring.
◦ Is not relieved by taking medicine under your tongue (sublingual nitroglycerin).
• You have profuse sweating without cause.
• You have unexplained:
◦ Heartburn or indigestion.
◦ Shortness of breath or difficulty breathing.
◦ Fluttering or fast heartbeat (palpitations).
◦ Nausea or vomiting.
◦ Fatigue.
◦ Feelings of nervousness or anxiety.
◦ Weakness.
◦ Diarrhea.
• You have sudden light-headedness or dizziness.
• You faint.
• You feel like hurting yourself or think about taking your own life.
These symptoms may represent a serious problem that is an emergency. Do not wait to see if the symptoms will go away. Get medical help right away. Call your local emergency services (911 in the U.S.). Do not drive yourself to the hospital.
Summary
• Coronary artery disease (CAD) is a condition in which the arteries that lead to the heart (coronary arteries) become narrow or blocked. The narrowing or blockage can lead to a heart attack.
• Many people do not have any symptoms during the early stages of CAD.
• CAD can be treated with lifestyle changes, medicines, surgery, or a combination of these treatments.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.

Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm
An aneurysm is a bulge in one of the blood vessels that carry blood away from the heart (artery). It happens when blood pushes up against a weak or damaged place in the wall of an artery. An abdominal aortic aneurysm happens in the main artery of the body (aorta).
Some aneurysms may not cause problems. If it grows, it can burst or tear, causing bleeding inside the body. This is an emergency. It needs to be treated right away.
What are the causes?
The exact cause of this condition is not known.
What increases the risk?
The following may make you more likely to get this condition:
• Being a male who is 60 years of age or older.
• Being white (Caucasian).
• Using tobacco.
• Having a family history of aneurysms.
• Having the following conditions:
◦ Hardening of the arteries (arteriosclerosis).
◦ Inflammation of the walls of an artery (arteritis).
◦ Certain genetic conditions.
◦ Being very overweight (obesity).
◦ An infection in the wall of the aorta (infectious aortitis).
◦ High cholesterol.
◦ High blood pressure (hypertension).
What are the signs or symptoms?
Symptoms depend on the size of the aneurysm and how fast it is growing. Most grow slowly and do not cause any symptoms. If symptoms do occur, they may include:
• Pain in the belly (abdomen), side, or back.
• Feeling full after eating only small amounts of food.
• Feeling a throbbing lump in the belly.
Symptoms that the aneurysm has burst (ruptured) include:
• Sudden, very bad pain in the belly, side, or back.
• Feeling sick to your stomach (nauseous).
• Throwing up (vomiting).
• Feeling light-headed or passing out.
How is this treated?
Treatment for this condition depends on:
• The size of the aneurysm.
• How fast it is growing.
• Your age.
• Your risk of having it burst.
If your aneurysm is smaller than 2 inches (5 cm), your doctor may manage it by:
• Checking it often to see if it is getting bigger. You may have an imaging test (ultrasound) to check it every 3–6 months, every year, or every few years.
• Giving you medicines to:
◦ Control blood pressure.
◦ Treat pain.
◦ Fight infection.
If your aneurysm is larger than 2 inches (5 cm), you may need surgery to fix it.
Follow these instructions at home:
Lifestyle
• Do not use any products that have nicotine or tobacco in them. This includes cigarettes, e-cigarettes, and chewing tobacco. If you need help quitting, ask your doctor.
• Get regular exercise. Ask your doctor what types of exercise are best for you.
Eating and drinking
• Eat a heart-healthy diet. This includes eating plenty of:
◦ Fresh fruits and vegetables.
◦ Whole grains.
◦ Low-fat (lean) protein.
◦ Low-fat dairy products.
• Avoid foods that are high in saturated fat and cholesterol. These foods include red meat and some dairy products.
• Do not drink alcohol if:
◦ Your doctor tells you not to drink.
◦ You are pregnant, may be pregnant, or are planning to become pregnant.
• If you drink alcohol:
◦ Limit how much you use to:
▪ 0–1 drink a day for women.
▪ 0–2 drinks a day for men.
◦ Be aware of how much alcohol is in your drink. In the U.S., one drink equals any of these:
▪ One typical bottle of beer (12 oz).
▪ One-half glass of wine (5 oz).
▪ One shot of hard liquor (1½ oz).
General instructions
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your doctor.
• Keep your blood pressure within normal limits. Ask your doctor what your blood pressure should be.
• Have your blood sugar (glucose) level and cholesterol levels checked regularly. Keep your blood sugar level and cholesterol levels within normal limits.
• Avoid heavy lifting and activities that take a lot of effort. Ask your doctor what activities are safe for you.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your doctor. This is important.
◦ Talk to your doctor about regular screenings to see if the aneurysm is getting bigger.
Contact a doctor if you:
• Have pain in your belly, side, or back.
• Have a throbbing feeling in your belly.
• Have a family history of aneurysms.
Get help right away if you:
• Have sudden, bad pain in your belly, side, or back.
• Feel sick to your stomach.
• Throw up.
• Have trouble pooping (constipation).
• Have trouble peeing (urinating).
• Feel light-headed.
• Have a fast heart rate when you stand.
• Have sweaty skin that is cold to the touch (clammy).
• Have shortness of breath.
• Have a fever.
These symptoms may be an emergency. Do not wait to see if the symptoms will go away. Get medical help right away. Call your local emergency services (911 in the U.S.). Do not drive yourself to the hospital.
Summary
• An aneurysm is a bulge in one of the blood vessels that carry blood away from the heart (artery). Some aneurysms may not cause problems.
• You may need to have yours checked often. If it grows, it can burst or tear. This causes bleeding inside the body. It needs to be treated right away.
• Follow instructions from your doctor about healthy lifestyle changes.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your doctor. This is important.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.

Chronic Kidney Disease, Adult
Chronic kidney disease (CKD) occurs when the kidneys become damaged slowly over a long period of time. The kidneys are a pair of organs that do many important jobs in the body, including:
• Removing waste and extra fluid from the blood to make urine.
• Making hormones that maintain the amount of fluid in tissues and blood vessels.
• Maintaining the right amount of fluids and chemicals in the body.
A small amount of kidney damage may not cause problems, but a large amount of damage may make it hard or impossible for the kidneys to work the way they should. If steps are not taken to slow down kidney damage or to stop it from getting worse, the kidneys may stop working permanently (end-stage renal disease or ESRD). Most of the time, CKD does not go away, but it can often be controlled. People who have CKD are usually able to live normal lives.
What are the causes?
The most common causes of this condition are diabetes and high blood pressure (hypertension). Other causes include:
• Heart and blood vessel (cardiovascular) disease.
• Kidney diseases, such as:
◦ Glomerulonephritis.
◦ Interstitial nephritis.
◦ Polycystic kidney disease.
◦ Renal vascular disease.
• Diseases that affect the immune Reyes.
• Genetic diseases.
• Medicines that damage the kidneys, such as anti-inflammatory medicines.
• Being around or being in contact with poisonous (toxic) substances.
• A kidney or urinary infection that occurs again and again (recurs).
• Vasculitis. This is swelling or inflammation of the blood vessels.
• A problem with urine flow that may be caused by:
◦ Cancer.
◦ Having kidney stones more than one time.
◦ An enlarged prostate, in males.
What increases the risk?
You are more likely to develop this condition if you:
• Are older than age 60.
• Are female.
• Are African-American, Hispanic, Asian, Pacific Islander, or American Indian.
• Are a current or former smoker.
• Are obese.
• Have a family history of kidney disease or failure.
• Often take medicines that are damaging to the kidneys.
What are the signs or symptoms?
Symptoms of this condition include:
• Swelling (edema) of the face, legs, ankles, or feet.
• Tiredness (lethargy) and having less energy.
• Nausea or vomiting.
• Confusion or trouble concentrating.
• Problems with urination, such as:
◦ Painful or burning feeling during urination.
◦ Decreased urine production.
◦ Frequent urination, especially at night.
◦ Bloody urine.
• Muscle twitches and cramps, especially in the legs.
• Shortness of breath.
• Weakness.
• Loss of appetite.
• Metallic taste in the mouth.
• Trouble sleeping.
• Dry, itchy skin.
• A low blood count (anemia).
• Pale lining of the eyelids and surface of the eye (conjunctiva).
Symptoms develop slowly and may not be obvious until the kidney damage becomes severe. It is possible to have kidney disease for years without having any symptoms.
How is this diagnosed?
This condition may be diagnosed based on:
• Blood tests.
• Urine tests.
• Imaging tests, such as an ultrasound or CT scan.
• A test in which a sample of tissue is removed from the kidneys to be examined under a microscope (kidney biopsy).
These test results will help your health care provider determine how serious the CKD is.
How is this treated?
There is no cure for most cases of this condition, but treatment usually relieves symptoms and prevents or slows the progression of the disease. Treatment may include:
• Making diet changes, which may require you to avoid alcohol, salty foods (sodium), and foods that are high in potassium, calcium, and protein.
• Medicines:
◦ To lower blood pressure.
◦ To control blood glucose.
◦ To relieve anemia.
◦ To relieve swelling.
◦ To protect your bones.
◦ To improve the balance of electrolytes in your blood.
• Removing toxic waste from the body through types of dialysis, if the kidneys can no longer do their job (kidney failure).
• Managing any other conditions that are causing your CKD or making it worse.
Follow these instructions at home:
Medicines
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your health care provider. The dose of some medicines that you take may need to be adjusted.
• Do not take any new medicines unless approved by your health care provider. Many medicines can worsen your kidney damage.
• Do not take any vitamin and mineral supplements unless approved by your health care provider. Many nutritional supplements can worsen your kidney damage.
General instructions
• Follow your prescribed diet as told by your health care provider.
• Do not use any products that contain nicotine or tobacco, such as cigarettes and e-cigarettes. If you need help quitting, ask your health care provider.
• Monitor and track your blood pressure at home. Report changes in your blood pressure as told by your health care provider.
• If you are being treated for diabetes, monitor and track your blood sugar (blood glucose) levels as told by your health care provider.
• Maintain a healthy weight. If you need help with this, ask your health care provider.
• Start or continue an exercise plan. Exercise at least 30 minutes a day, 5 days a week.
• Keep your immunizations up to date as told by your health care provider.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your health care provider. This is important.
Where to find more information
• American Association of Kidney Patients: https://www.davis-stewart.com/
• National Kidney Foundation: https://www.gonzalez.com/
• American Kidney Fund: http://www.carter.org/
• Life Options Rehabilitation Program: https://jones.com/ and https://watkins.biz/
Contact a health care provider if:
• Your symptoms get worse.
• You develop new symptoms.
Get help right away if:
• You develop symptoms of ESRD, which include:
◦ Headaches.
◦ Numbness in the hands or feet.
◦ Easy bruising.
◦ Frequent hiccups.
◦ Chest pain.
◦ Shortness of breath.
◦ Lack of menstruation, in women.
• You have a fever.
• You have decreased urine production.
• You have pain or bleeding when you urinate.
Summary
• Chronic kidney disease (CKD) occurs when the kidneys become damaged slowly over a long period of time.
• The most common causes of this condition are diabetes and high blood pressure (hypertension).
• There is no cure for most cases of this condition, but treatment usually relieves symptoms and prevents or slows the progression of the disease. Treatment may include a combination of medicines and lifestyle changes.

Hematoma
A hematoma is a collection of blood. A hematoma can happen:
• Under the skin.
• In an organ.
• In a body space.
• In a joint space.
• In other tissues.
The blood can thicken (clot) to form a lump that you can see and feel. The lump is often hard and may become sore and tender. The lump can be very small or very big. Most hematomas get better in a few days to weeks. However, some hematomas may be serious and need medical care.
What are the causes?
This condition is caused by:
• An injury.
• Blood that leaks under the skin.
• Problems from surgeries.
• Medical conditions that cause bleeding or bruising.
What increases the risk?
You are more likely to develop this condition if:
• You are an older adult.
• You use medicines that thin your blood.
What are the signs or symptoms?
Symptoms depend on where the hematoma is in your body.
• If the hematoma is under the skin, there is:
◦ A firm lump on the body.
◦ Pain and tenderness in the area.
◦ Bruising. The skin above the lump may be blue, dark blue, purple-red, or yellowish.
• If the hematoma is deep in the tissues or body spaces, there may be:
◦ Blood in the stomach. This may cause pain in the belly (abdomen), weakness, passing out (fainting), and shortness of breath.
◦ Blood in the head. This may cause a headache, weakness, trouble speaking or understanding speech, or passing out.
How is this diagnosed?
This condition is diagnosed based on:
• Your medical history.
• A physical exam.
• Imaging tests, such as ultrasound or CT scan.
• Blood tests.
How is this treated?
Treatment depends on the cause, size, and location of the hematoma. Treatment may include:
• Doing nothing. Many hematomas go away on their own without treatment.
• Surgery or close monitoring. This may be needed for large hematomas or hematomas that affect the body's organs.
• Medicines. These may be given if a medical condition caused the hematoma.
Follow these instructions at home:
Managing pain, stiffness, and swelling
• If told, put ice on the area.
◦ Put ice in a plastic bag.
◦ Place a towel between your skin and the bag.
◦ Leave the ice on for 20 minutes, 2–3 times a day for the first two days.
• If told, put heat on the affected area after putting ice on the area for two days. Use the heat source that your doctor tells you to use. This could be a moist heat pack or a heating pad. To do this:
◦ Place a towel between your skin and the heat source.
◦ Leave the heat on for 20–30 minutes.
◦ Remove the heat if your skin turns bright red. This is very important if you are unable to feel pain, heat, or cold. You may have a greater risk of getting burned.
• Raise (elevate) the affected area above the level of your heart while you are sitting or lying down.
• Wrap the affected area with an elastic bandage, if told by your doctor. Do not wrap the bandage too tightly.
• If your hematoma is on a leg or foot and is painful, your doctor may give you crutches. Use them as told by your doctor.
General instructions
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your doctor.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your doctor. This is important.
Contact a doctor if:
• You have a fever.
• The swelling or bruising gets worse.
• You start to get more hematomas.
Get help right away if:
• Your pain gets worse.
• Your pain is not getting better with medicine.
• Your skin over the hematoma breaks or starts to bleed.
• Your hematoma is in your chest or belly and you:
◦ Pass out.
◦ Feel weak.
◦ Become short of breath.
• You have a hematoma on your scalp that is caused by a fall or injury, and you:
◦ Have a headache that gets worse.
◦ Have trouble speaking or understanding speech.
◦ Become less alert or you pass out.
Summary
• A hematoma is a collection of blood in any part of your body.
• Most hematomas get better on their own in a few days to weeks. Some may need medical care.
• Follow instructions from your doctor about how to care for your hematoma.
• Contact a doctor if the swelling or bruising gets worse, or if you are short of breath.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.
